A policy analyst is analyzing two economic models represented by the following systems of differential equations:

Model 1: 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dx}{dt} &= 3x - 4y \\
\frac{dy}{dt} &= 2x - 3y
\end{align*}

Model 2: 
\begin{align*}
\frac{du}{dt} &= 4u - 5v \\
\frac{dv}{dt} &= 3u - 4v
\end{align*}

The policy analyst wants to know if these two systems are topologically equivalent. A system of equations is said to be topologically equivalent if there exist homeomorphisms \(f(t, x, y) = (T(t), X(t, x, y), Y(t, x, y))\) and \(g(t, u, v) = (T'(t), U(t, u, v), V(t, u, v))\) such that \(f\) transforms the first system into the second and \(g\) transforms the second system into the first. 

Find such homeomorphisms \(f\) and \(g\) if they exist. If they do not exist, provide a proof why.
